       <narrative xml:lang="EN">50%
CEDAW 8th and 9th report developed
120 youth supporting implementation of SDG 16</narrative>
      </comment>
     </target>
     <actual>
      <comment>
       <narrative xml:lang="EN">30%
100 (67 women, 33 Men) community health management committee members, community health volunteers and community health officers in Ga central and Accra Metro have improved knowledge and skills to strengthen equitable and essential health service provision for the vulnerable within their communities 

104 (43 women, 61Men) community leaders, 100 women leaders and 100 (45 women, 55 Men) young persons have increased knowledge and capacity to support the uptake of essential health service for the vulnerable within Ga central and Accra Metro districts 

52 (26 women, 26 Men) Regional and National leaders of the National Association of Persons living with HIV (NAP +) have strengthened capacities to support effective implementation of prevailing anti stigma provisions and strategies with their improved knowledge of the Ghana AIDS Commission Act 938, Ghana AIDS Commission Regulations and the legislative instrument 

120 youth (50 women and 70 men) from across Ghana are better positioned to contribute and participate in governance and peace towards the achievement of SDG 16

UNDP supported a national dialogue to promote peace and issue a consensus document dubbed &#x201C;ADA DECLARATION&#x201D; as a step to restore trust in the electoral system

The Convention on the Elimination of All Forms of Discrimination against Women is considered as the principal legal framework for assessing discrimination against women and girls as it provides robust standards on equality and non-discrimination for all women, in all fields. Inputs for the finalisation of a comprehensive national 8th and 9th CEDAW reports has been provided through support from UNDP, to the Ministry of Gender, Children and Social Protection</narrative>
      </comment>
